        <section classes="classref-introduction-group" ids="description" names="description">
            <title>Description</title>
            <paragraph>A <reference internal="True" refuri="class_texture2d#class-texture2d"><inline classes="std std-ref">Texture2D</inline></reference> based on an <reference internal="True" refuri="class_image#class-image"><inline classes="std std-ref">Image</inline></reference>. For an image to be displayed, an <strong>ImageTexture</strong> has to be created from it using the <reference internal="True" refid="class-imagetexture-method-create-from-image"><inline classes="std std-ref">create_from_image()</inline></reference> method:</paragraph>
            <literal_block force="False" language="gdscript" linenos="False" xml:space="preserve">var image = Image.load_from_file("res://icon.svg")
var texture = ImageTexture.create_from_image(image)
$Sprite2D.texture = texture</literal_block>
            <paragraph>This way, textures can be created at run-time by loading images both from within the editor and externally.</paragraph>
            <paragraph><strong>Warning:</strong> Prefer to load imported textures with <reference internal="True" refuri="class_@gdscript#class-gdscript-method-load"><inline classes="std std-ref">@GDScript.load()</inline></reference> over loading them from within the filesystem dynamically with <reference internal="True" refuri="class_image#class-image-method-load"><inline classes="std std-ref">Image.load()</inline></reference>, as it may not work in exported projects:</paragraph>
            <literal_block force="False" language="gdscript" linenos="False" xml:space="preserve">var texture = load("res://icon.svg")
$Sprite2D.texture = texture</literal_block>
            <paragraph>This is because images have to be imported as a <reference internal="True" refuri="class_compressedtexture2d#class-compressedtexture2d"><inline classes="std std-ref">CompressedTexture2D</inline></reference> first to be loaded with <reference internal="True" refuri="class_@gdscript#class-gdscript-method-load"><inline classes="std std-ref">@GDScript.load()</inline></reference>. If you'd still like to load an image file just like any other <reference internal="True" refuri="class_resource#class-resource"><inline classes="std std-ref">Resource</inline></reference>, import it as an <reference internal="True" refuri="class_image#class-image"><inline classes="std std-ref">Image</inline></reference> resource instead, and then load it normally using the <reference internal="True" refuri="class_@gdscript#class-gdscript-method-load"><inline classes="std std-ref">@GDScript.load()</inline></reference> method.</paragraph>
            <paragraph><strong>Note:</strong> The image can be retrieved from an imported texture using the <reference internal="True" refuri="class_texture2d#class-texture2d-method-get-image"><inline classes="std std-ref">Texture2D.get_image()</inline></reference> method, which returns a copy of the image:</paragraph>
            <literal_block force="False" language="gdscript" linenos="False" xml:space="preserve">var texture = load("res://icon.svg")
var image = texture.get_image()</literal_block>
            <paragraph>An <strong>ImageTexture</strong> is not meant to be operated from within the editor interface directly, and is mostly useful for rendering images on screen dynamically via code. If you need to generate images procedurally from within the editor, consider saving and importing images as custom texture resources implementing a new <reference internal="True" refuri="class_editorimportplugin#class-editorimportplugin"><inline classes="std std-ref">EditorImportPlugin</inline></reference>.</paragraph>
            <paragraph><strong>Note:</strong> The maximum texture size is 16384Ã—16384 pixels due to graphics hardware limitations.</paragraph>
